2026-04-02 10:59:21 - Agent_20260402105130 - INFO - [*] Tool call: complete_review
2026-04-02 10:59:21 - Agent_20260402105130 - INFO - [+] Agent signaled completion: Reviewed 10 CodeQL findings (Query UUID: 20260402102016) for HTTP input flowing to ResourceHelper.resolveMandatoryResourceAsInputStream() with file: prefix injection enabling filesystem traversal. All 10 findings were confirmed as true positives.

The root vulnerability is in ResourceHelper.resolveResourceAsInputStream() which directly opens a FileInputStream for any URI starting with "file:" without any path canonicalization, containment check, or access control. The method strips the "file:" prefix and passes the remainder directly to new FileInputStream(uri).

Multiple HTTP input paths reach this sink:
1. ResourceEndpoint.java:106 - via LanguageEndpoint/LanguageProducer (Exchange.LANGUAGE_SCRIPT header)
2. LanguageSupport.java:67 - via SimpleLanguage expression loading (resource:file: pattern)
3. ResourceHelper.java:176 - direct sink (the core vulnerability)
4. ResourceHelper.java:198 - CamelContext-based overload used by multiple callers
5. ScriptBuilder.java:533 - via camel-script language evaluation
6. SqlHelper.java:37 - via SqlStoredProducer reading body as SQL query
7. PGPDataFormatUtil.java:188 - via PGP key filename from message headers
8. HazelcastDefaultComponent.java:153 - via hazelcastConfigUri endpoint parameter (server mode)
9. HazelcastDefaultComponent.java:205 - via hazelcastConfigUri endpoint parameter (client mode)
10. XmlSignatureProcessor.java:106 - via HEADER_SCHEMA_RESOURCE_URI message header (most direct)

All paths lack path validation. An attacker can inject file:///etc/passwd, file:../../../etc/shadow, or URL-encoded traversal sequences to read arbitrary server files.
